**(1)** Clouds, Landscapes and Rivers are only "externals", displaying simulation results. The raw sim itself is generated by NinjaLive Actor - and you could unhide the raw data by selecting *NinajLiveComponent /LiveGeneric* - and set "*TraceMeshInvisible*" to FALSE + assign a debug material (eg.: *MI_DensityBuffer_Red* ) to the tracemesh -- by adding it to the "OutputMaterials" array
**(2)** Ninja is feeding the raw sim data to user provided MATERIAL INSTANCES (1st and 2nd Output Materials) - and then, assigns the Mat.Instances to user defined external objects - based on TAGS (explained here: https://youtu.be/vXalfRAnXak?t=3724)
**(3)** while most Unreal Object types are DIRECTLY accessible for ninja, Landscape Components (including Landscape Spline) ARE NOT. To overcome this problem, I have created a small additional utility ( *\Content\FluidNinjaLive\UseCases\017_RiverAndLandscape\BP_NinjaLiveLandscapeUtility* ) that helps ninja to acces Landscape Components (explained here: https://youtu.be/UBNjhb4J8I0?list=PLVCUepYV6TvMXN8HQjLU9wKz-G_6JvJsF&t=781 + https://youtu.be/UBNjhb4J8I0?list=PLVCUepYV6TvMXN8HQjLU9wKz-G_6JvJsF&t=1652 + inside the utility blueprint, as comment )
**(4)** the utility is made to handle landscapes. You need to create a modified version of it (the blueprint) that works on Landscape Splines - by adjusting the "Get Components by Class" node - and use "LandscapeSplinesComponent" instead of "LandscapeComponent" (see SCREENSHOT https://ibb.co/TvQWhF5)
